An evaluation of an Extension for Community Healthcare Outcomes (ECHO) 
intervention in cancer prevention and survivorship care.

Milgrom ZZ(1)(2), Severance TS(3)(4), Scanlon CM(3), Carson AT(2), Janota AD(2), 
Vik TA(3)(4), Duwve JM(2)(5), Dixon BE(1)(2), Mendonca EA(6)(7).

Author information:
(1)Center for Biomedical Informatics, Regenstrief Institute, 1101 West Tenth 
Street, Indianapolis, IN, 46202, USA.
(2)Richard M. Fairbanks School of Public Health, Indiana University, 1050 
Wishard Boulevard, Indianapolis, IN, 46202, USA.
(3)Riley Hospital for Children, 705 Riley Hospital Drive, Indianapolis, IN, 
46202, USA.
(4)Indiana University School of Medicine, 340 West Tenth Street, Fairbanks Hall, 
Suite 6200, Indianapolis, IN, 46202, USA.
(5)Kansas Department of Health and Environment, Curtis State Office Building, 
1000 SW Jackson St, Topeka, KS, 66612, USA.
(6)Center for Biomedical Informatics, Regenstrief Institute, 1101 West Tenth 
Street, Indianapolis, IN, 46202, USA. emendonc@iu.edu.
(7)Indiana University School of Medicine, 340 West Tenth Street, Fairbanks Hall, 
Suite 6200, Indianapolis, IN, 46202, USA. emendonc@iu.edu.

To improve cancer care in Indiana, a telementoring program using the Extension 
for Community Healthcare Outcomes (ECHO) model was introduced in September 2019 
to promote best-practice cancer prevention, screening, and survivorship care by 
primary care providers (PCPs). The aim of this study was to evaluate the 
program's educational outcomes in its pilot year, using Moore's Evaluation 
Framework for Continuing Medical Education and focusing on the program's impact 
on participants' knowledge, confidence, and professional practice. We collected 
data in 22 semi-structured interviews (13 PCPs and 9 non-PCPs) and 30 anonymous 
one-time surveys (14 PCPs and 16 non-PCPs) from the program participants (hub 
and spoke site members), as well as from members of the target audience who did 
not participate. In the first year, average attendance at each session was 2.5 
PCPs and 12 non-PCP professionals. In spite of a relatively low PCP 
participation, the program received very positive satisfaction scores, and 
participants reported improvements in knowledge, confidence, and practice. Both 
program participants and target audience respondents particularly valued three 
features of the program: its conversational format, the real-life experiences 
gained, and the support received from a professional interdisciplinary 
community. PCPs reported preferring case discussions over didactics. Our results 
suggest that the Cancer ECHO program has benefits over other PCP-targetted 
cancer control interventions and could be an effective educational means of 
improving cancer control capacity among PCPs and others. Further study is 
warranted to explain the discrepancies among study participants' perceptions of 
the program's strengths and the relatively low PCP participation before 
undertaking a full-scale effectiveness study.

